The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Hyderabad, June 3: K. Chandrasekhar Rao today resigned as Telengana Rashtra Samiti chief, taking responsibility for the drubbing in the May bypolls.           
	The TRS won two of the four Lok Sabha seats and only seven of the 18 Assembly seats, losing some of its strongholds to the Congress and the Telugu Desam Party.          In his resignation letter, Rao asked the party working committee, which would meet tomorrow, to accept his resignation. I will remain a true soldier of the party and carry on the movement till I achieve (the separate state of) Telengana, he wrote.                  
	 Mumbai: Mukesh Ambani has been asked by the Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai to halt construction of a helipad atop his residence Sea Wind, the 20-storey building in Cuffe Parade. The Reliance Industries chairman has been told to get the requisite clearances first. The civic authorities have also imposed on Ambani a fine of Rs 2.43 lakh, calculated on the basis of the construction work completed.                   
	 New Delhi: The urban development ministry has written to all states asking them to make road infrastructure and transport accessible to people with disabilities. The secretary urban development M. Ramachandran has also directed states to appoint a nodal officer in every district to ensure that public places and transport are inclusive.                  
	Jaipur (PTI): A day labourer from Rajasthan, who cracked the IIT JEE this year but could not afford the fees of the premier institution, has been offered an education loan of Rs 4 lakh by a bank. Rakesh Kumar Bunkar, who works at a fruit sellers stall on Rs 60 a day, could not deposit the IIT fees. Punjab National Bank offered him the loan for a BTech course when his story hit newspapers here.                  
	Amritsar (PTI): Five robbers drove off a bank cash van containing Rs 37 lakh after injuring the guard on Tuesday. The robbers car intercepted the cash van outside a State Bank of India branch at 11.30am. They hijacked the vehicle at gunpoint.
                                                                                                                         
